1
00:02:26,700 --> 00:02:29,020
<i>What happens
when the light first pierces</i>

2
00:02:29,101 --> 00:02:31,498
<i>the dark dampness
in which we have waited?</i>

3
00:02:33,181 --> 00:02:35,338
<i>We are slapped and cut loose.</i>

4
00:02:37,301 --> 00:02:40,772
<i>If we are lucky,
someone is there to catch us,</i>

5
00:02:40,941 --> 00:02:43,626
<i>and persuade us
that we are safe.</i>

6
00:02:45,701 --> 00:02:47,225
<i>But are we safe?</i>

7
00:02:48,461 --> 00:02:51,980
<i>What happens if, too early,
we lose a parent?</i>

8
00:02:52,702 --> 00:02:56,624
<i>That party on whom we rely
for only everything?</i>

9
00:02:57,741 --> 00:03:00,061
<i>Why, we are cut loose again,</i>

10
00:03:01,021 --> 00:03:03,543
<i>and we wonder, even dread,</i>

11
00:03:04,501 --> 00:03:06,658
<i>whose hands will catch us now.</i>

12
00:03:11,821 --> 00:03:14,583
<i>There once lived a man
named Nicholas Nickleby.</i>

13
00:03:15,462 --> 00:03:17,101
<i>Unambitious in business,</i>

14
00:03:17,182 --> 00:03:20,222
<i>he devoted himself
to the happiness of his family.</i>

15
00:03:20,942 --> 00:03:24,701
<i>But he is not the Nicholas Nickleby
you have come to hear about.</i>

16
00:03:25,262 --> 00:03:27,985
<i>That Nicholas Nickleby
is here.</i>

17
00:03:29,222 --> 00:03:30,622
<i>And here.</i>

18
00:03:32,782 --> 00:03:34,268
<i>And here.</i>

19
00:03:34,342 --> 00:03:35,387
Said your prayers?

20
00:03:35,462 --> 00:03:36,737
Yes.

21
00:03:36,942 --> 00:03:38,821
I prayed that
I should have this day,

22
00:03:38,862 --> 00:03:40,588
the same day
we had today,

23
00:03:40,622 --> 00:03:42,185
all the rest
of my life.

24
00:03:42,743 --> 00:03:45,744
But someday you will find
someone who will have

25
00:03:45,822 --> 00:03:48,382
a greater hold
on your affections than I do.

26
00:03:49,863 --> 00:03:52,385
The most important
journey of your life

27
00:03:52,903 --> 00:03:54,590
will be to find her.

28
00:03:55,103 --> 00:03:57,865
<i>Nicholas had
a younger sister, Kate.</i>

29
00:03:58,262 --> 00:03:59,863
<i>Here she is again.</i>

30
00:04:00,622 --> 00:04:02,348
<i>And here.</i>

31
00:04:02,382 --> 00:04:04,185
<i>Goodness, how it goes.</i>

32
00:04:05,343 --> 00:04:09,380
<i>For their father,
these children were a divine burden.</i>

33
00:04:09,423 --> 00:04:11,379
<i>Never had money meant less to him,</i>

34
00:04:11,543 --> 00:04:14,458
<i>and never
had he needed it more.</i>

35
00:04:15,703 --> 00:04:16,901
<i>His wife said...</i>

36
00:04:16,943 --> 00:04:18,228
Speculate.

37
00:04:18,983 --> 00:04:21,898
<i>Since it was well known that
Mr. Nickleby's brother, Ralph,</i>

38
00:04:21,983 --> 00:04:23,536
<i>many years his senior,</i>

39
00:04:23,623 --> 00:04:27,142
<i>had made his fortune in London
by just this method,</i>

40
00:04:27,863 --> 00:04:31,862
<i>so Nicholas Nickleby,
who had never speculated,</i>

41
00:04:32,783 --> 00:04:34,058
<i>speculated.</i>

42
00:04:35,144 --> 00:04:37,378
<i>It is a particular
sort of triumph</i>

43
00:04:37,423 --> 00:04:40,539
<i>that bankers have made
the word "speculation"</i>

44
00:04:40,624 --> 00:04:42,829
<i>synonymous with "adventure, "</i>

45
00:04:42,863 --> 00:04:46,382
<i>when, indeed, it means only
that one may gain a great deal,</i>

46
00:04:46,463 --> 00:04:48,745
<i>or one may lose a great deal.</i>

47
00:04:48,783 --> 00:04:51,986
<i>Alas, for Mr. Nickleby,
it meant the latter.</i>

48
00:04:53,823 --> 00:04:57,179
<i>Four stockbrokers
took villa residences in Italy,</i>

49
00:04:57,263 --> 00:04:59,948
<i>and 400 nobodies were ruined.</i>

50
00:05:01,264 --> 00:05:03,508
<i>Eliminating all he had saved,</i>

51
00:05:03,543 --> 00:05:06,343
<i>as well as any wish
to earn it again,</i>

52
00:05:06,384 --> 00:05:08,302
<i>Mr. Nickleby took to his bed</i>

53
00:05:08,784 --> 00:05:12,428
<i>until he surrendered
to the one certainty of life</i>

54
00:05:12,464 --> 00:05:16,146
<i>which no amount of speculation
can prevent.</i>

55
00:05:17,264 --> 00:05:18,817
What shall we do?

56
00:05:30,224 --> 00:05:33,264
<i>Here is Nicholas Nickleby again.</i>

57
00:05:37,665 --> 00:05:39,381
<i>Nineteen years old,</i>

58
00:05:39,865 --> 00:05:42,665
<i>and head of his family.</i>

59
00:05:56,305 --> 00:05:57,753
Come here!

60
00:06:03,145 --> 00:06:05,417
Said he would
join me at the tavern.

61
00:06:06,545 --> 00:06:08,223
Turnips and carrots!

62
00:06:08,385 --> 00:06:10,063
Mind your back, Miss.

63
00:06:10,105 --> 00:06:11,908
Turnips and carrots...

64
00:06:12,465 --> 00:06:15,025
Iron gates
and wheels mended.

65
00:06:43,346 --> 00:06:44,669
Please, Mr. Nickleby,

66
00:06:44,746 --> 00:06:47,066
do you wish my father
to go to debtor's prison?

67
00:06:47,146 --> 00:06:48,939
Where your father
sleeps, Miss Bray,

68
00:06:49,026 --> 00:06:50,339
is of no concern to me.

69
00:06:50,386 --> 00:06:53,550
Father tells me that the interest
is what makes the debt so unmanageable.

70
00:06:53,586 --> 00:06:54,784
Could you not stop it?

71
00:06:54,866 --> 00:06:56,621
Tell your father
to repay the loan,

72
00:06:56,666 --> 00:06:58,948
and that will stop
the interest right away.

73
00:07:16,626 --> 00:07:19,148
You must bear up
against sorrow, ma'am.

74
00:07:20,227 --> 00:07:21,588
I always do.

75
00:07:21,627 --> 00:07:23,468
Mine was no common loss.

76
00:07:24,107 --> 00:07:26,274
Well, it was no uncommon loss.

77
00:07:26,947 --> 00:07:29,737
Husbands die every day.

78
00:07:30,667 --> 00:07:31,827
And wives.

79
00:07:32,307 --> 00:07:33,630
And brothers also.

80
00:07:33,907 --> 00:07:35,710
Yes, and puppies, too.

81
00:07:36,947 --> 00:07:37,906
Ma'am, you did not mention

82
00:07:37,987 --> 00:07:39,828
what my brother's
complaint was.

83
00:07:40,187 --> 00:07:43,668
We feel he died
of a broken heart.

84
00:07:43,707 --> 00:07:45,346
Pooh,
there's no such thing.

85
00:07:45,787 --> 00:07:48,347
Indeed, if you have
no heart to break.

86
00:07:49,587 --> 00:07:50,670
In your letter,
you said,

87
00:07:50,708 --> 00:07:52,587
uh, the creditors
had administered

88
00:07:52,628 --> 00:07:53,913
and there was nothing
left for you?

89
00:07:54,187 --> 00:07:56,306
We tried to
sell the house,

90
00:07:56,347 --> 00:07:58,907
but no one seemed
to want a little home like ours.

91
00:07:58,987 --> 00:08:00,626
So you spent what
little remained,

92
00:08:00,667 --> 00:08:02,220
coming all the way
to London,

93
00:08:02,307 --> 00:08:03,707
to see what I could
do for you?

94
00:08:05,147 --> 00:08:07,784
It was your brother's
dying wish

95
00:08:07,828 --> 00:08:10,072
that you might
do something for his children.

96
00:08:10,148 --> 00:08:12,747
How is it, when a man dies
without any property of his own,

97
00:08:12,788 --> 00:08:15,147
he thinks he has the right
to dispose of other people's?

98
00:08:15,188 --> 00:08:17,585
What a feckless, inconsiderate man.

99
00:08:17,628 --> 00:08:20,428
Our father,
your brother, had a noble heart.

100
00:08:20,788 --> 00:08:22,514
Which beats no more.

101
00:08:23,748 --> 00:08:24,870
You, girl,

102
00:08:25,828 --> 00:08:27,985
you haven't
been brought up too delicately

103
00:08:28,068 --> 00:08:30,667
to apprentice at some
boarding school, have you?

104
00:08:30,708 --> 00:08:31,868
Uncle,

105
00:08:32,228 --> 00:08:35,671
I will try to do
anything to gain me a home and bread.

106
00:08:38,868 --> 00:08:42,541
Now that I think of it, I know a
dressmaker who may have some work.

107
00:08:44,709 --> 00:08:46,905
You, boy, have you
ever done anything?

108
00:08:47,828 --> 00:08:48,863
No.

109
00:08:49,109 --> 00:08:51,477
Noggs, where is
the morning paper that I left on my desk?

110
00:08:51,508 --> 00:08:53,301
- On my desk.
- Bring it to me.

111
00:08:53,389 --> 00:08:54,865
"Bring it to me."
"Bring it to me."

112
00:08:55,149 --> 00:08:56,232
Stop parroting me.

113
00:08:56,308 --> 00:08:58,830
I wish I was a parrot.
I'd fly away.

114
00:08:58,869 --> 00:09:01,228
I wish you were a parrot, too.
I'd wring your neck.

115
00:09:02,588 --> 00:09:03,786
Read that.

116
00:09:03,828 --> 00:09:05,113
What is it, Nicholas?

117
00:09:05,549 --> 00:09:07,102
An advertisement.

118
00:09:07,869 --> 00:09:10,420
"Education at Mr. Wackford
Squeers' Academy."

119
00:09:12,669 --> 00:09:13,954
Oh, no, no.

120
00:09:16,789 --> 00:09:17,748
"Dotheboys Hall,

121
00:09:17,789 --> 00:09:20,388
"at the delightful village
of Dotheboys, in Yorkshire.

122
00:09:20,749 --> 00:09:22,782
"Youth are clothed,
boarded and booked,

123
00:09:22,870 --> 00:09:25,142
"instructed in
all languages, living and dead,

124
00:09:25,229 --> 00:09:26,830
"mathematics, orthography,

125
00:09:26,869 --> 00:09:28,624
"the use of globes
and single stick.

126
00:09:29,229 --> 00:09:32,307
"Diet unparalleled.
An able assistant wanted.

127
00:09:32,789 --> 00:09:34,831
"Annual salary 5 pounds.

128
00:09:35,149 --> 00:09:36,827
"Master of Arts preferred."

129
00:09:38,949 --> 00:09:40,512
I'm not a Master of Arts.

130
00:09:40,869 --> 00:09:42,758
That can be got over, I believe.

131
00:09:42,870 --> 00:09:44,471
But it is such a long way off.

132
00:09:44,790 --> 00:09:46,909
If I am fortunate enough
to be appointed to the post,

133
00:09:46,990 --> 00:09:48,908
what will become
of those I leave behind?

134
00:09:49,109 --> 00:09:50,585
It will be
my immediate care

135
00:09:50,670 --> 00:09:53,432
to place your mother and sister
in some sphere of life

136
00:09:53,510 --> 00:09:55,639
in which they may
become independent.

137
00:09:56,790 --> 00:09:59,437
I will not forget what you have
done for me this day, uncle.

138
00:10:00,470 --> 00:10:01,831
Nor shall I.

139
00:10:11,270 --> 00:10:13,274
Any chimneys to sweep?

140
00:10:15,230 --> 00:10:18,155
There he is.
He's the man with one eye.

141
00:10:18,230 --> 00:10:20,992
Though the popular prejudice
runs in favor of two.

142
00:10:21,870 --> 00:10:23,826
Is this one inch milk
and the rest water?

143
00:10:23,871 --> 00:10:25,108
Aye, sir.

144
00:10:26,550 --> 00:10:28,065
Here's richness.

145
00:10:28,671 --> 00:10:30,550
When I say "number one,"
you may take a drink.

146
00:10:30,631 --> 00:10:33,153
When I say "number two,"
the boy next to you may take it,

147
00:10:33,231 --> 00:10:36,635
and so on,
till all five boys have been nourished.

148
00:10:36,710 --> 00:10:40,105
But work fast.
We leave when the coach horn blows.

149
00:10:40,151 --> 00:10:41,426
Number one.

150
00:10:41,991 --> 00:10:43,141
Number two.

151
00:10:44,311 --> 00:10:45,519
Number three.

152
00:10:46,591 --> 00:10:47,991
Number four.

153
00:10:49,191 --> 00:10:50,274
Number five.

154
00:10:51,351 --> 00:10:52,837
Out you go. Out you go.

155
00:10:53,591 --> 00:10:57,513
Subdue your appetites,
and you've conquered human nature.

156
00:10:57,591 --> 00:10:59,633
Yorkshire coach
leaves in 5 minutes!

157
00:11:00,471 --> 00:11:03,031
Wait by the coach
in a straight line.

158
00:11:03,431 --> 00:11:05,109
Ah, Squeers,
this is the boy I told you about.

159
00:11:05,192 --> 00:11:06,227
My nephew.

160
00:11:06,272 --> 00:11:08,717
I am most grateful
for the opportunity to serve, sir.

161
00:11:09,791 --> 00:11:11,430
- Mr. Squeers.
- Ah, Mrs. Shaygar.

162
00:11:11,511 --> 00:11:12,987
Could you give
those to Henry?

163
00:11:13,071 --> 00:11:14,557
Tuesday is
his birthday.

164
00:11:14,591 --> 00:11:18,072
Delighted, my dear.
The boy's happiness is our prime concern.

165
00:11:18,111 --> 00:11:20,470
Three inside,
two little ones up top.

166
00:11:21,912 --> 00:11:24,232
Get up behind.
If a boy drops off the back,

167
00:11:24,312 --> 00:11:26,076
that's 20 pounds
a year lost.

168
00:11:28,752 --> 00:11:29,950
If he is the schoolmaster,

169
00:11:30,031 --> 00:11:31,824
what kind of school
can it be?

170
00:11:32,792 --> 00:11:34,240
I hardly know.

171
00:11:36,952 --> 00:11:38,198
Bless you both.

172
00:11:40,712 --> 00:11:41,757
Goodbye.

173
00:11:45,272 --> 00:11:46,710
Someday,
we will once again

174
00:11:46,752 --> 00:11:49,475
share the protection
of the same roof,

175
00:11:49,552 --> 00:11:52,237
and revive the happiness
denied to us now.

176
00:11:53,593 --> 00:11:54,878
I promise.

177
00:11:58,113 --> 00:12:01,306
Psst!
Young man. Young man.

178
00:12:05,753 --> 00:12:07,594
Forgive me. I know the world.

179
00:12:08,432 --> 00:12:09,592
Your father didn't,

180
00:12:09,633 --> 00:12:11,186
or he wouldn't have
done me a kindness

181
00:12:11,233 --> 00:12:12,470
when there was
no hope of a return.

182
00:12:12,552 --> 00:12:14,796
You don't, or you
wouldn't be bound

183
00:12:14,872 --> 00:12:16,310
on... On such a journey.

184
00:12:17,193 --> 00:12:19,993
If ever you should need
help or shelter in London...

185
00:12:20,273 --> 00:12:23,073
Oh, dear.
I once thought I never should.

186
00:12:24,153 --> 00:12:25,428
They know where I live,

187
00:12:25,513 --> 00:12:27,987
at the sign
of the Crown in Golden Square.

188
00:12:28,433 --> 00:12:29,957
You can come at night.

189
00:12:30,273 --> 00:12:32,795
Once, nobody was ashamed.

190
00:12:32,873 --> 00:12:34,071
Ashamed?

191
00:12:34,153 --> 00:12:36,272
Where are you, Nickleby? Up, up.

192
00:12:36,313 --> 00:12:38,346
If you should go
near Barnard Castle,

193
00:12:38,393 --> 00:12:40,186
there's good ale
at the King's Head.

194
00:12:40,273 --> 00:12:41,270
Say you know me,

195
00:12:41,314 --> 00:12:43,836
and I'm sure they won't
charge you for it.

196
00:12:43,914 --> 00:12:45,112
And...

197
00:12:46,313 --> 00:12:48,873
You may say
"Mr. Noggs" there,

198
00:12:49,394 --> 00:12:51,312
for I was
a gentleman then.

199
00:12:51,673 --> 00:12:53,034
I was.

200
00:13:01,874 --> 00:13:03,034
Walk on.

201
00:13:03,114 --> 00:13:04,274
Goodbye, Nicholas.

202
00:13:23,234 --> 00:13:24,356
Whoa!

203
00:13:36,114 --> 00:13:37,111
Smike!

204
00:13:40,194 --> 00:13:41,431
Smike!

205
00:13:45,274 --> 00:13:46,472
Smike!

206
00:13:47,155 --> 00:13:49,360
Is this Dotheboys Hall?

207
00:13:49,674 --> 00:13:51,831
No need to call it
a hall up here.

208
00:13:52,435 --> 00:13:54,554
We call it that in London,
because it sounds better.

209
00:13:55,315 --> 00:13:56,638
Hurry, lad! Hurry.

210
00:14:15,155 --> 00:14:16,794
Where the devil were you?

211
00:14:17,115 --> 00:14:18,275
Please, sir,

212
00:14:19,395 --> 00:14:21,236
I fell asleep over the fire.

213
00:14:21,275 --> 00:14:23,356
Missus said
I might go in there for a warm.

214
00:14:24,596 --> 00:14:26,274
You'd have been
a deuced deal more wakeful

215
00:14:26,356 --> 00:14:27,957
out in the cold.

216
00:14:31,596 --> 00:14:33,677
Is that my Squeery?

217
00:14:40,115 --> 00:14:42,723
The crime
of my dead eye, my love,

218
00:14:42,796 --> 00:14:44,915
is that I can't see you twice.

219
00:14:45,595 --> 00:14:46,592
How's the pig?

220
00:14:46,676 --> 00:14:47,826
Just as you left her.

221
00:14:47,876 --> 00:14:48,911
And the boys?

222
00:14:48,956 --> 00:14:51,353
Young Braithwaite's
had a fever.

223
00:14:51,916 --> 00:14:53,632
Third time this year.

224
00:14:53,716 --> 00:14:55,355
I say it's obstinacy,

225
00:14:55,396 --> 00:14:57,592
and we beat it out of him.

226
00:14:57,636 --> 00:14:59,477
No one can cure an illness

227
00:14:59,516 --> 00:15:01,002
quicker than you, my love.

228
00:15:03,436 --> 00:15:05,392
This is the new man,
Mr. Nickleby.

229
00:15:07,117 --> 00:15:08,670
I hope you're not hungry.

230
00:15:08,757 --> 00:15:09,955
I am.

231
00:15:10,036 --> 00:15:11,359
Of course you are.

232
00:15:11,436 --> 00:15:14,274
I've got a nice hot stew
for you here, Squeery.

233
00:15:14,716 --> 00:15:16,317
And there's bread
on the table.

234
00:15:18,717 --> 00:15:20,241
I brought the letters
to the boys,

235
00:15:20,316 --> 00:15:21,792
I'll read them
in the morning.

236
00:15:21,877 --> 00:15:23,037
I'm doing
the brimstone first.

237
00:15:23,117 --> 00:15:24,239
Of course you are.
Of course you are.

238
00:15:24,316 --> 00:15:25,562
That's right...

239
00:15:25,796 --> 00:15:27,675
Grand piece of meat
in that, Squeery.

240
00:15:27,757 --> 00:15:29,233
Put the heat back in you.

241
00:15:29,277 --> 00:15:30,725
Aye, it will.

242
00:15:31,077 --> 00:15:32,160
How was
your journey, my pet?

243
00:15:32,197 --> 00:15:33,232
Dreadful.

244
00:15:33,277 --> 00:15:34,312
Was it perishing?

245
00:15:34,397 --> 00:15:35,442
Torture.

246
00:15:39,037 --> 00:15:40,475
What?

247
00:15:44,117 --> 00:15:45,555
Have you...

248
00:15:46,797 --> 00:15:48,475
Did anybody...

249
00:15:50,557 --> 00:15:52,561
Has nothing been heard...

250
00:15:55,357 --> 00:15:56,632
About me?

251
00:15:57,317 --> 00:16:00,596
Not a word,
and never will we.

252
00:16:01,357 --> 00:16:02,440
But count your blessings.

253
00:16:02,518 --> 00:16:04,081
You've been here
all these years...

254
00:16:05,317 --> 00:16:07,800
And not a penny paid
after the first six.

255
00:16:07,838 --> 00:16:09,756
No clue as to who
you belong to,

256
00:16:09,797 --> 00:16:11,082
and still I feed you.

257
00:16:11,997 --> 00:16:13,713
That's cause for joy.

258
00:16:15,877 --> 00:16:17,756
And here's more
cause for joy.

259
00:16:19,557 --> 00:16:20,717
Little Wackford.

260
00:16:24,757 --> 00:16:25,917
Father!

261
00:16:27,998 --> 00:16:29,877
Look what your pa
brought you.

262
00:16:30,558 --> 00:16:31,555
Eh?

263
00:18:06,600 --> 00:18:07,846
<i>"Dear Kate,</i>

264
00:18:07,879 --> 00:18:11,034
<i>"My first morning here began with the
news that the pump had frozen,</i>

265
00:18:11,080 --> 00:18:12,767
<i>"but events
soon distracted me."</i>

266
00:18:12,800 --> 00:18:13,797
Smike!

267
00:18:13,880 --> 00:18:15,241
Who are you after?

268
00:18:15,320 --> 00:18:18,715
It's brimstone morning,
and I can't find the school spoon.

269
00:18:18,760 --> 00:18:21,761
We purify the boys' blood
now and then, Nickleby.

270
00:18:21,841 --> 00:18:24,324
Purify, fiddlesticks!

271
00:18:25,880 --> 00:18:29,198
We give the boys
brimstone and treacle, Mr. Knuckleboy,

272
00:18:29,280 --> 00:18:31,802
because if we didn't,
they'd always be ailing.

273
00:18:32,720 --> 00:18:34,283
Because it spoils
their appetites

274
00:18:34,360 --> 00:18:36,594
and comes cheaper than
breakfast and dinner.

275
00:18:36,641 --> 00:18:39,997
You might say it does
them good and us good at the same time.

276
00:18:40,601 --> 00:18:41,914
Smike!

277
00:18:45,121 --> 00:18:46,243
Where's the school spoon?

278
00:18:46,280 --> 00:18:47,277
Please, ma'am.

279
00:18:47,361 --> 00:18:49,000
Huh? Huh?

280
00:18:49,081 --> 00:18:50,241
Please.

281
00:18:57,081 --> 00:18:59,200
Don't contradict
your mistress.

282
00:19:00,481 --> 00:19:01,689
Take it.

283
00:19:02,361 --> 00:19:03,684
Take it.
Be thankful.

284
00:19:04,481 --> 00:19:06,993
A most invaluable
woman that, Nickleby.

285
00:19:07,041 --> 00:19:08,642
I don't know her equal.

286
00:19:08,681 --> 00:19:09,803
Nor I.

287
00:19:09,881 --> 00:19:10,878
No, please!

288
00:19:10,921 --> 00:19:11,956
Take it.

289
00:19:12,322 --> 00:19:13,482
And thank me for it.

290
00:19:13,562 --> 00:19:15,125
She does things
for them boys,

291
00:19:15,202 --> 00:19:16,841
that I don't believe
half the mothers going

292
00:19:16,921 --> 00:19:18,714
would do for
their own sons.

293
00:19:19,442 --> 00:19:21,925
- I should think they would not, sir.
- No.

294
00:19:22,162 --> 00:19:24,243
<i>"Mr. Squeers'
return from London</i>

295
00:19:24,321 --> 00:19:25,366
<i>"is a great event,</i>

296
00:19:25,442 --> 00:19:27,360
<i>"as he brings the boys
news from home."</i>

297
00:19:27,402 --> 00:19:29,003
Bolder, come here.

298
00:19:33,922 --> 00:19:35,207
No letters.

299
00:19:35,681 --> 00:19:37,522
But I saw your father
in London.

300
00:19:37,602 --> 00:19:40,201
He was 2.10 pounds
short in his payments.

301
00:19:40,802 --> 00:19:43,439
One. Two. Three.

302
00:19:43,562 --> 00:19:45,882
Four. Five. Six.

303
00:19:46,802 --> 00:19:48,844
But the good news is,
we'll keep you on.

304
00:19:48,922 --> 00:19:50,446
Smike, take him out.

305
00:19:51,522 --> 00:19:53,727
Letter for Cobbey.
Stand up.

306
00:19:56,002 --> 00:19:57,277
Your grandmother's dead.

307
00:19:58,683 --> 00:20:01,166
Your uncle's took to drink.

308
00:20:01,242 --> 00:20:04,157
That's all the news
your sister sends, except for 8 pence,

309
00:20:05,482 --> 00:20:08,359
which will just cover
the square of glass you broke last week.

310
00:20:08,442 --> 00:20:10,120
<i>"After this, classes began."</i>

311
00:20:10,203 --> 00:20:11,488
Where's Graymarsh?

312
00:20:11,523 --> 00:20:13,920
Please, sir, he's
cleaning the back parlor window.

313
00:20:13,962 --> 00:20:17,405
Perfect.
C-L-E-A-N, "clean."

314
00:20:17,443 --> 00:20:19,485
Verb, active,
"to make bright."

315
00:20:19,523 --> 00:20:20,999
"Winder," a casement.

316
00:20:21,082 --> 00:20:24,160
"Win," W-I-N, "der," D-E-R.

317
00:20:24,243 --> 00:20:26,765
When the boy knows this,
he goes and does it.

318
00:20:26,843 --> 00:20:27,850
Where's Dorn?

319
00:20:27,922 --> 00:20:29,763
Please, sir,
he's weeding the garden.

320
00:20:29,843 --> 00:20:31,166
To be sure.

321
00:20:31,202 --> 00:20:35,517
"Bot," B-O-T,
"tin," T-I-N, "ney," N-E-Y.

322
00:20:35,603 --> 00:20:38,163
"Bottiney."
Noun, substantive.

323
00:20:38,243 --> 00:20:41,446
Knowledge of plants,
which he's applying right now.

324
00:20:41,483 --> 00:20:42,921
That's our system,
Nickleby.

325
00:20:43,003 --> 00:20:44,086
What do you think of it?

326
00:20:44,163 --> 00:20:45,122
It's useful.

327
00:20:45,603 --> 00:20:47,290
<i>"And so went the day.</i>

328
00:20:48,683 --> 00:20:51,838
<i>"I very much hope
I can be of service here."</i>

329
00:21:02,243 --> 00:21:03,691
Are you cold?

330
00:21:04,644 --> 00:21:06,523
You're shivering, poor fellow.

331
00:21:14,804 --> 00:21:16,002
There.

332
00:21:21,724 --> 00:21:23,363
Oh, dear, my heart.

333
00:21:25,444 --> 00:21:27,199
I feel lost here, too.

334
00:21:29,084 --> 00:21:30,963
But we must always hope.

335
00:21:32,924 --> 00:21:34,170
Hope?

336
00:21:36,764 --> 00:21:39,363
Do you remember
the boy who died here?

337
00:21:39,444 --> 00:21:40,489
I was not here.

338
00:21:41,284 --> 00:21:42,607
What of him?

339
00:21:43,244 --> 00:21:44,442
I...

340
00:21:45,925 --> 00:21:48,006
I was with him
that night.

341
00:21:49,564 --> 00:21:53,198
He began to see faces
around his bed that came from home.

342
00:21:57,045 --> 00:21:59,835
He said they smiled
and talked to him.

343
00:22:02,725 --> 00:22:05,918
At last, he died...

344
00:22:07,925 --> 00:22:10,408
Lifting his head
to kiss them.

345
00:22:15,005 --> 00:22:16,328
Yes?

346
00:22:19,925 --> 00:22:22,447
What faces
will smile on me when I die?

347
00:22:24,805 --> 00:22:27,202
Who will comfort me
that long night?

348
00:22:30,206 --> 00:22:31,922
They cannot come
from home.

349
00:22:32,165 --> 00:22:33,287
They would frighten me
if they did,

350
00:22:33,325 --> 00:22:35,051
for I shouldn't
know them.

351
00:22:38,286 --> 00:22:39,638
No.

352
00:22:40,646 --> 00:22:42,247
There is no hope.

353
00:22:43,486 --> 00:22:44,886
No hope for me at all!

354
00:22:44,966 --> 00:22:46,289
What's the matter, love?

355
00:22:46,366 --> 00:22:48,888
Tilda's getting married
to John Browdie.

356
00:22:48,966 --> 00:22:51,891
I'll be the only girl in the
county who hasn't posted my banns.

357
00:22:51,966 --> 00:22:55,130
John Browdie's no catch.
I hate him.

358
00:22:55,205 --> 00:22:56,844
Eat your breakfast.

359
00:22:57,125 --> 00:22:58,841
I'll never eat again.

360
00:22:59,366 --> 00:23:01,600
How do you like
Mr. Knuckleboy?

361
00:23:01,646 --> 00:23:03,966
I hate him,
that's how I like him.

362
00:23:04,326 --> 00:23:07,366
He's a nasty, stuck-up monkey.

363
00:23:07,926 --> 00:23:10,170
He needs his pride
brought down.

364
00:23:10,246 --> 00:23:12,087
I'll leave that
to you, my love.

365
00:23:12,166 --> 00:23:13,690
There's not a woman
in all England

366
00:23:13,766 --> 00:23:16,566
can bring a person's
pride down quicker than you can.

367
00:23:16,646 --> 00:23:18,046
Oh.

368
00:23:18,326 --> 00:23:19,879
Thank you, Squeery.

369
00:23:21,606 --> 00:23:23,361
Who's Mr. Knuckleboy?

370
00:23:23,407 --> 00:23:24,730
The new teacher.

371
00:23:24,807 --> 00:23:26,408
A smile like
a sugar-drop

372
00:23:26,486 --> 00:23:29,094
and the straightest legs
I've ever seen.

373
00:23:32,727 --> 00:23:34,290
<i>The word for "window"</i>

374
00:23:34,367 --> 00:23:37,205
is <i>"fenetre, "</i>
F-E-N-E...

375
00:23:37,287 --> 00:23:38,926
Oh, father.

376
00:23:39,366 --> 00:23:41,293
Oh, I beg your pardon.

377
00:23:41,327 --> 00:23:43,206
I thought
my father was here.

378
00:23:43,727 --> 00:23:45,606
I'm so foolish,
I'm sure.

379
00:23:45,647 --> 00:23:47,171
Not at all.

380
00:23:47,647 --> 00:23:51,368
Again, the word
for "window" is <i>"fenetre."</i>

381
00:23:51,407 --> 00:23:54,888
No, I'm sure
I am foolish.

382
00:23:55,607 --> 00:23:59,683
It's just my pen is in need of...

383
00:24:04,168 --> 00:24:05,616
Mending.

384
00:24:06,407 --> 00:24:08,488
Oh, well, may I be of service?

385
00:24:08,528 --> 00:24:11,606
No, no, I couldn't,
I just couldn't.

386
00:24:11,688 --> 00:24:13,567
Well, all right.

387
00:24:16,167 --> 00:24:17,567
<i>Tilda!</i>

388
00:24:18,008 --> 00:24:19,158
Tilda!

389
00:24:20,247 --> 00:24:21,723
What is it, Fanny?

390
00:24:21,767 --> 00:24:23,445
I am engaged!

391
00:24:27,208 --> 00:24:28,368
To whom?

392
00:24:28,768 --> 00:24:30,609
To the new schoolteacher.

393
00:24:30,688 --> 00:24:31,800
The speed of it!

394
00:24:31,848 --> 00:24:33,401
What's he said?

395
00:24:33,448 --> 00:24:35,692
We don't need language.

396
00:24:35,768 --> 00:24:38,050
If you could have
only seen his looks.

397
00:24:38,088 --> 00:24:41,454
- Did he look at you like this?
- Yes.

398
00:24:41,488 --> 00:24:43,204
If he did,
you're engaged.

399
00:24:43,288 --> 00:24:44,649
That's how John
looked at me.

400
00:24:44,688 --> 00:24:46,088
Hope it was
better than that.

401
00:24:46,168 --> 00:24:47,328
Thee'd have run
to the hills.

402
00:24:47,369 --> 00:24:49,929
Hush, John!
So, when is the day?

403
00:24:49,969 --> 00:24:54,572
Well, we just need
a final declaration to settle it,

404
00:24:54,608 --> 00:24:56,727
but he's shy
in the way of words.

405
00:24:56,809 --> 00:24:58,688
Oh, Fanny,
I'm so happy for you.

406
00:25:43,689 --> 00:25:46,096
Have you read
<i>The Pilgrim's Progress?</i>

407
00:26:18,970 --> 00:26:21,492
<i>"The Pilgrim's Progress,</i>
by John Bunyan.

408
00:26:22,730 --> 00:26:24,609
"As I walked
through the wilderness

409
00:26:24,650 --> 00:26:26,692
"of this world,
I lighted on a certain"...

410
00:26:26,730 --> 00:26:29,089
What do you think
you're doing, eh?

411
00:26:29,531 --> 00:26:30,691
Eh?

412
00:26:31,451 --> 00:26:32,937
Get on with your work!

413
00:26:35,250 --> 00:26:38,405
Don't give me that
high-and-mighty look.

414
00:26:39,050 --> 00:26:40,450
He don't pay.

415
00:26:40,970 --> 00:26:43,530
Therefore, he works.

416
00:26:54,011 --> 00:26:54,970
Ladies.

417
00:26:59,251 --> 00:27:01,571
Quick, quick,
I must do something

418
00:27:01,611 --> 00:27:03,135
to engage his sympathy,

419
00:27:03,211 --> 00:27:05,733
and bring him
to the declaration. Should I choke?

420
00:27:05,771 --> 00:27:08,849
I think fainting
might be more romantic than choking.

421
00:27:11,211 --> 00:27:12,208
Oh!

422
00:27:12,291 --> 00:27:14,094
Oh, Mr. Nickleby,
help!

423
00:27:18,291 --> 00:27:19,374
What's happened?

424
00:27:19,452 --> 00:27:21,811
I think she was undone
by your coldness just now.

425
00:27:21,891 --> 00:27:24,653
Was I abrupt?
My mind, I'm afraid, was on other matters.

426
00:27:24,731 --> 00:27:26,092
I'm sure
it wasn't deliberate.

427
00:27:26,452 --> 00:27:27,976
It's just that
with all the feelings

428
00:27:28,011 --> 00:27:31,406
that have been so nearly
expressed between you of late...

429
00:27:35,372 --> 00:27:39,620
If I caused any distress,
I reproach myself most bitterly, but...

430
00:27:40,972 --> 00:27:42,736
This is most awkward,
but...

431
00:27:43,532 --> 00:27:45,335
Well, does your friend
think I'm in love with her?

432
00:27:45,691 --> 00:27:47,973
Does she think so?
Of course.

433
00:27:48,452 --> 00:27:50,456
But I've made
no such declaration.

434
00:27:50,732 --> 00:27:52,496
Your eyes said
what your mouth could not.

435
00:27:53,612 --> 00:27:56,652
Perhaps my mouth
should say what my eyes have not.

436
00:27:56,972 --> 00:27:59,369
I have scarcely seen
the young lady three times,

437
00:27:59,692 --> 00:28:02,051
but should I have
seen her 30 or 30,000,

438
00:28:02,092 --> 00:28:03,607
it would still
be the same.

439
00:28:03,692 --> 00:28:07,019
I have not one thought,
hope or wish connected with her,

440
00:28:07,053 --> 00:28:09,412
unless it be
part of the picture I keep in my mind

441
00:28:09,773 --> 00:28:13,216
of one day being able to turn my
back upon this accursed place,

442
00:28:13,292 --> 00:28:14,778
and never
to think of it again

443
00:28:14,853 --> 00:28:17,452
with any feeling
but loathing and disgust.

444
00:28:19,373 --> 00:28:22,413
Refused by a teacher

445
00:28:22,493 --> 00:28:24,008
picked up
by an advertisement.

446
00:28:24,652 --> 00:28:26,090
He's insulted not just you,

447
00:28:26,132 --> 00:28:28,011
but the whole
house of Squeers.

448
00:28:28,052 --> 00:28:29,260
Smike!

449
00:28:29,292 --> 00:28:32,169
He's proud.
I said so from the start.

450
00:28:33,333 --> 00:28:34,608
He must be wounded.

451
00:28:34,693 --> 00:28:36,812
I hate him like poison!

452
00:28:36,893 --> 00:28:38,494
Where is Smike?
We need wood.

453
00:28:38,573 --> 00:28:42,255
He's with Mr. Nickleby.
He waits on him hand and foot.

454
00:28:47,893 --> 00:28:49,216
Well,

455
00:28:49,933 --> 00:28:51,409
he must not have
enough to do.

456
00:28:52,493 --> 00:28:56,453
<i>We must think of how
better to occupy our Smike.</i>

457
00:29:10,254 --> 00:29:12,085
<i>They are so hard on me.</i>

458
00:29:13,774 --> 00:29:15,126
But for you,

459
00:29:16,654 --> 00:29:18,293
they would kill me.

460
00:29:21,934 --> 00:29:24,724
I fear they
may be killing you because of me.

461
00:29:27,814 --> 00:29:30,086
You will do better
when I am gone.

462
00:29:30,174 --> 00:29:31,411
Gone?

463
00:29:33,134 --> 00:29:34,572
Are you going?

464
00:29:35,254 --> 00:29:37,776
I would go tomorrow
if I could.

465
00:29:40,014 --> 00:29:41,327
Tell me,

466
00:29:42,254 --> 00:29:44,536
is the world
as bad as this place?

467
00:29:45,214 --> 00:29:46,652
Oh, no.

468
00:29:47,295 --> 00:29:49,337
Should I ever
meet you there?

469
00:29:50,335 --> 00:29:51,572
Why, yes,
I'm sure at some...

470
00:29:51,654 --> 00:29:52,661
No.

471
00:29:52,974 --> 00:29:54,335
No, tell me.

472
00:29:55,734 --> 00:29:58,371
Tell me that
I should be sure to find you.

473
00:30:01,775 --> 00:30:03,050
You would.

474
00:30:04,614 --> 00:30:06,934
And I would help you
and aid you,

475
00:30:07,894 --> 00:30:11,375
and not bring fresh sorrow on you,
as I have done here.

476
00:30:14,894 --> 00:30:16,006
Smike!

477
00:30:17,135 --> 00:30:18,659
Smike!

478
00:30:20,215 --> 00:30:21,500
Smike!

479
00:30:21,575 --> 00:30:23,541
He is not here, sir!

480
00:30:26,295 --> 00:30:27,417
Smike!

481
00:30:27,855 --> 00:30:29,293
Show yourself!

482
00:30:37,175 --> 00:30:39,131
Who knows where he is?

483
00:30:41,576 --> 00:30:44,050
Please, sir,
I think he's run away.

484
00:30:44,135 --> 00:30:45,851
And what
possible reason

485
00:30:45,935 --> 00:30:49,732
would any boy
have to run away from my establishment?

486
00:30:51,255 --> 00:30:52,770
Do you think
he's run away?

487
00:30:52,816 --> 00:30:54,292
I hope so!

488
00:30:54,376 --> 00:30:55,459
Squeery,

489
00:30:57,896 --> 00:30:59,862
we best go find him.

490
00:31:07,576 --> 00:31:10,568
But if you lift
one finger

491
00:31:11,336 --> 00:31:13,608
to stop what's
about to begin,

492
00:31:15,176 --> 00:31:19,136
you and I will
fall out in a way

493
00:31:20,856 --> 00:31:23,215
that will spoil
your beauty.

494
00:31:29,776 --> 00:31:33,257
Take pattern by Smike
if you dare, boys!

495
00:31:35,256 --> 00:31:37,778
You'll see what he'll get for hisself
when he's brought back.

496
00:31:40,817 --> 00:31:42,811
For brought back
he will be.

497
00:31:43,977 --> 00:31:47,496
You go the north way, Squeery,
I'll take the west.

498
00:31:53,577 --> 00:31:54,814
Mr. Squeers!

499
00:31:54,897 --> 00:31:56,536
Mr. Squeers, please!

500
00:31:56,937 --> 00:31:58,538
I beg you,
forgive the boy!

501
00:31:58,577 --> 00:32:00,140
He is not in
his right mind.

502
00:32:00,177 --> 00:32:02,660
That will soon be
the least of his problems.

503
00:32:08,578 --> 00:32:11,100
Father, please
don't let them find him.

504
00:32:11,537 --> 00:32:13,579
If they do,
let him be dead,

505
00:32:13,618 --> 00:32:15,536
his last breath
a free one.

506
00:33:08,658 --> 00:33:10,978
Does he have him?
Is it Smike?

507
00:33:41,099 --> 00:33:42,863
Is she back with him?

508
00:33:43,939 --> 00:33:45,905
Then you do not have him.

509
00:33:45,940 --> 00:33:47,138
Thank God.

510
00:34:06,900 --> 00:34:08,338
Squeery!

511
00:34:10,060 --> 00:34:12,016
Squeery, we have him!

512
00:34:18,100 --> 00:34:20,142
Is every boy here?

513
00:34:20,540 --> 00:34:21,901
Get back!

514
00:34:23,820 --> 00:34:25,776
And you, Nickleby.

515
00:34:36,900 --> 00:34:38,578
Have you anything to say?

516
00:34:40,980 --> 00:34:43,742
Please, sir, spare me.

517
00:34:44,180 --> 00:34:46,855
Oh, I'll spare you, Smike.

518
00:34:46,900 --> 00:34:48,348
I'll spare you.

519
00:34:50,060 --> 00:34:52,102
I'll flog you
to within an inch of your life,

520
00:34:52,181 --> 00:34:53,936
and I'll spare you then.

521
00:35:03,141 --> 00:35:04,263
Stop!

522
00:35:08,221 --> 00:35:09,947
This must not go on.

523
00:35:11,101 --> 00:35:12,654
I will not allow it.

524
00:35:13,981 --> 00:35:17,145
You dare
to challenge my authority!

525
00:35:17,461 --> 00:35:18,659
Stay back!

526
00:35:20,261 --> 00:35:22,102
Touch him at your peril!

527
00:35:22,581 --> 00:35:24,853
I will not stand by
and see it done.

528
00:35:25,821 --> 00:35:27,537
You will do
as you're told!

529
00:35:27,621 --> 00:35:28,982
If you raise
the devil within me,

530
00:35:29,062 --> 00:35:31,862
the consequences shall
fall on your own head!

531
00:35:32,222 --> 00:35:34,025
Once I begin, God help you!

532
00:35:38,262 --> 00:35:39,422
Ah! Ah!

533
00:35:39,502 --> 00:35:41,141
Stop! Stop! Stop!

534
00:35:44,822 --> 00:35:46,663
No, please, wait!

535
00:35:46,742 --> 00:35:48,017
Wait, wait.

536
00:35:52,182 --> 00:35:54,944
I do not know why,
but I am going to show you

537
00:35:55,021 --> 00:35:57,668
what you have
never shown any boy in this room.

538
00:36:01,062 --> 00:36:02,423
Pity.

539
00:36:39,783 --> 00:36:41,586
Wait. I say, wait!

540
00:36:48,663 --> 00:36:49,823
I've come from
the schoolhouse.

541
00:36:50,303 --> 00:36:53,947
Mr. Squeers says he was attacked.
Beaten, and nearly senseless.

542
00:36:53,983 --> 00:36:55,661
When he said
it was thee who did it,

543
00:36:55,703 --> 00:36:57,342
I knew thee must not
be allowed to leave...

544
00:36:57,463 --> 00:36:58,978
We will not be stopped!

545
00:36:59,063 --> 00:37:00,376
Without my
shaking your hand,

546
00:37:00,463 --> 00:37:02,620
and saying to thee,
"Job well done."

547
00:37:02,943 --> 00:37:04,784
Give us thee hand,
will you, huh?

548
00:37:05,344 --> 00:37:07,262
Whoever heard
the like of it?

549
00:37:07,703 --> 00:37:09,141
I only wish

550
00:37:09,223 --> 00:37:11,860
I could've been
there to see it myself.

551
00:37:17,504 --> 00:37:19,057
What do thee
mean to do now?

552
00:37:19,543 --> 00:37:21,182
I don't know.

553
00:37:21,264 --> 00:37:22,261
How much cash
has thee got?

554
00:37:23,464 --> 00:37:24,662
Not much.
But I'll find...

555
00:37:24,744 --> 00:37:25,712
Take what you need.

556
00:37:25,784 --> 00:37:26,743
No. I could not.

557
00:37:26,783 --> 00:37:27,828
Please.

558
00:37:29,864 --> 00:37:31,062
Every boy in that room

559
00:37:31,144 --> 00:37:32,419
would add to it if he could.

560
00:37:33,584 --> 00:37:34,984
Thank you.

561
00:37:35,864 --> 00:37:38,741
Here, and take this
bit of timber, too, to help thee on.

562
00:37:39,944 --> 00:37:41,747
You keep a good heart.

563
00:37:42,384 --> 00:37:44,503
God bless thee. Huh, huh!

564
00:37:46,664 --> 00:37:48,505
Beating the schoolmaster!

565
00:37:50,304 --> 00:37:53,018
God, it's the best thing
I've heard in 20 years.

566
00:38:06,065 --> 00:38:07,388
Tomorrow...

567
00:38:08,344 --> 00:38:09,945
Where will you go?

568
00:38:10,745 --> 00:38:12,500
Perhaps to Liverpool.

569
00:38:13,144 --> 00:38:15,186
I could find
work on a ship.

570
00:38:18,425 --> 00:38:20,026
Do not be anxious.

571
00:38:20,785 --> 00:38:23,259
Before I do anything,
I will get you to your home.

572
00:38:24,185 --> 00:38:25,546
Where is it?

573
00:38:30,545 --> 00:38:32,069
You are my home.

574
00:38:33,266 --> 00:38:34,589
Smike!

575
00:38:36,025 --> 00:38:38,461
Please, may I go
with you to the sea?

576
00:38:38,545 --> 00:38:40,463
I will be your faithful,
hard-working servant.

577
00:38:40,505 --> 00:38:43,104
I will. I promise I will.

578
00:38:44,185 --> 00:38:46,179
I want only to be near you.

579
00:38:50,226 --> 00:38:51,376
Smike...

580
00:38:52,225 --> 00:38:53,548
The word which
separates us

581
00:38:53,625 --> 00:38:55,543
shall never be
said by me.

582
00:38:56,546 --> 00:38:58,262
And I promise you,

583
00:38:58,346 --> 00:38:59,947
from this night forward...

584
00:39:00,585 --> 00:39:03,385
The world shall deal
by you as it does by me.

585
00:39:12,946 --> 00:39:14,739
Do you have a family...

586
